50|$|Crime scene {{investigators}} use <b>luminol</b> to find {{traces of}} blood, even {{if someone has}} cleaned or removed it. The investigator sprays a solution of <b>luminol</b> and the oxidant. The iron in blood catalyses the luminescence. The amount of catalyst necessary to cause the reaction is very small relative {{to the amount of}} <b>luminol,</b> allowing detection of even trace amounts of blood. The blue glow lasts for about 30 seconds per application. Detecting the glow requires a fairly dark room. Any glow detected may be documented by a long-exposure photograph.|$|E
